How to Finance the Green Transition
New York — This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global battle against climate change and submit new emission reduction commitments.
The climate crisis is serious, and our pace of action is far too slow.
We are still stuck in slow motion.
Accelerating the pace of change requires collaborative efforts from both public and private sectors.
Fortunately, through the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaboration to curb climate change is increasing.
Under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg, the UN Special Envoy for Climate Action, CFLI was established with the aim of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," which outlines how to expand green finance to support an orderly transition to a low-carbon economy, and proposes public-private partnership opportunities to achieve the objectives of the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, in response to the call from European heads of state and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, we are prepared to show greater ambition and strengthen the role of EIB as the EU's dedicated climate bank.
The EIB will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investments, and commit at least 1 trillion euros to low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, by 2025, at least 50% of EIB financing will be used for climate action and environmental sustainability.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the objectives of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, and among the most important issues is climate change.
The urgency of the climate crisis is matched by our determination.
This summer, European countries experienced record-breaking heat and crop failures due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars annually, and threaten even more lives.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, because funding new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues cities around the world.
Changing the investment model can accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This shift has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, half of the U.S. coal-fired power plants retired, while at the same time, the clean energy industry created 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 in the coal industry.
Additionally, an increasing number of U.S. cities and states have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from the Beyond Carbon initiative, launched last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies, aimed at supporting the full decarbonization of the US economy.
As an international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce investments in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investments toward electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive transformative change for the green transition.
These investments will yield huge returns, including reducing the massive costs to public health caused by air pollution.
We can also take numerous measures to guide necessary capital flows.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, businesses and investors have been unaware of climate-related risks, not knowing the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather impacts.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in more sustainable ways, allowing investors to reward those companies that take climate change seriously.
Secondly, we must clarify the investment risks related to green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a small number of cities in the developing world can obtain credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean public transport, energy-efficient buildings, and other projects that reduce emissions has been affected.
Governments and listed banks must increase their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by the Bloomberg Philanthropies Foundation.
Thirdly, we need to modernize the power grid.
Incentives such as refunds and tax benefits have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of batteries storage and other emerging technologies, helping to overcome intermittency issues more quickly.
Additionally, better grid connectivity could allow regions with surplus wind and solar power to supply electricity to regions experiencing shortages.
The government can play a leadership role in both areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has grown to $136 billion.
But compared to the global bond market of $100 trillion, this is just a drop in the bucket.
Therefore, EIB is helping the EU develop sustainable finance standard classifications, so investors can compare similar projects, just like standard bonds.
More and better information on carbon footprints can enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby encouraging more private investment to flow into low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
